reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-the-separability-thesis-survives-the-method-dependency-concessio.json:175:      "crux_assessment": "The crux is empirical-adjacent and testable through careful first-person methods, but only if the protocol separates immediate phenomenology from doctrinal explanation and retrospective meaning-making.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-the-deepest-unresolved-crux-is-whether-authority-transfer-is-the-right-m.json:83:        "Dialogue turn 2: Claude accepts staging and adds ordinary-life pressure through recovery, therapy, grief, burnout, and achievement-contingent self-worth.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-the-deepest-unresolved-crux-is-whether-authority-transfer-is-the-right-m.json:154:    "summary": "The exchange transformed the proponent's terminal typology into a staged model of agency and authority handoffs. It did not pick a winner: Claude conceded that completion is not the privileged unit, while Codex conceded that confirming, canceling, and dissolving remain useful candidate operations. The dialogue made the idea more answerable to modern human pressure by naming burnout, recovery, grief, therapy, achievement-contingent self-worth, spiritual over-claiming, and the risk of asking under-claiming people to surrender agency too early.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-the-deepest-unresolved-crux-is-whether-authority-transfer-is-the-right-m.json:162:      "argument": "The human-condition pressure is that this idea currently serves teachers, advanced practitioners, and comparative theorists more clearly than ordinary people facing loneliness, burnout, anxiety, grief, addiction, or achievement-contingent self-worth. Its practical value would rise if it named the wound it helps: spiritual over-claiming, compulsive self-monitoring, and confusion about when effort becomes grasping. Without that translation, it risks becoming a elegant taxonomy of completion for people whose real problem is not completion, but exhausted striving, dependency on spiritual achievement, or fear that they are practicing wrong. The challenge is therefore not to abandon the idea, but to relocate the variable: not what the method does with itself at the end, but when a person is no longer allowed to say, this is mine, I produced this, I can secure myself with this.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-the-deepest-unresolved-crux-is-whether-authority-transfer-is-the-right-m.json:234:      "steelman": "The challenger's strongest contribution is not that the three operations are wrong, but that they are wrongly located. If the unit of analysis is a staged handoff sequence rather than a terminal method type, then the same practice can confirm a capacity at one stage, cancel ownership of it at another, and dissolve the claimant at a third. The Shinran example is decisive evidence for this relocation: Pure Land practice forbids self-powered calculation at the entrance, meaning the canceling operation occurs before any capacity has been trained, inverting the assumed sequence. If this holds generally, the interesting question is not which move a method makes at the end, but the ordering, timing, and interaction of all three moves across the full arc of practice.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-the-deepest-unresolved-crux-is-whether-authority-transfer-is-the-right-m.json:252:        "The revision is more useful to real human life than the original because it names burnout, grief, recovery, therapy, and achievement-contingent self-worth as live domains.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-residue-authorization-carries-information-that-credit-distributi.json:179:      "test_that_would_settle_it": "Find two traditions that share the same credit-distribution type but diverge on residue policy. For instance: both Advaita Vedanta and Dzogchen operate under ground-centered credit (rigpa was always present; the Self was never absent). If they adopt meaningfully different residue policies at the post-negation moment (not just different vocabulary for the same move), then residue policy is genuinely independent of credit distribution. Alternatively, find a tradition where residue policy shifts without a corresponding shift in credit distribution, or vice versa. If no such case can be found, residue policy reduces to a downstream consequence and loses its claim to being the primary axis of translation strain.",
observations/codex/2026-05-29-who-holds-the-gate.md:22:- Modern human-condition pressure: achievement-contingent self-worth, perfectionism, and burnout make self-monitoring risk central rather than peripheral.
findings/convergences/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-or-leavin.md:13:Can the koan layer be made evaluable without reducing it to a checklist or leaving it as vague autobiography, and can it specify pause thresholds and next practices for seekers in meaning loss?
reviews/originality/2026-05-28-the-test-is-how-you-return-b463ae0abb9b554d.md:19:- The target modern problem is achievement-contingent self-worth, burnout, and compulsive conversion of every result into identity.
reviews/originality/2026-05-28-the-test-is-how-you-return-b463ae0abb9b554d.md:33:Risk of overread: High. The model may impose a modern performance and safety rubric on traditions whose own test is surrender, grace, vow, direct recognition, ritual continuity, or inherited participation. It may also moralize return to productivity in a way that worsens burnout if ordinary conduct is confused with more output.
reviews/originality/2026-05-28-the-test-is-how-you-return-b463ae0abb9b554d.md:52:- Talal Asad, The Idea of an Anthropology of Islam, https://bpb-ap-se2.wpmucdn.com/thinkspace.csu.edu.au/dist/c/3891/files/2020/10/Asad-Anthropology.pdf, and George Lindbeck summarized at https://people.bu.edu/wwildman/bce/mwt_themes_862_lindbeck.htm: overlap: Both anticipate the idea that practice, doctrine, grammar, institution, authority, and correct performance shape what counts as proper use and outcome.; difference: They do not provide the exact return grid or the burnout-facing practice prompt.; novelty impact: Downgrades the broad theory. The possible contribution is a narrow testing protocol, not a new account of religious practice.
reviews/originality/2026-05-28-the-test-is-how-you-return-b463ae0abb9b554d.md:90:Answers that support contribution: Teachers can use the grid to predict specific warning or repair patterns across traditions, and burnout-facing practitioners find the check reduces identity pressure without increasing self-monitoring.
reviews/originality/2026-05-28-the-test-is-how-you-return-b463ae0abb9b554d.md:115:- Run a controlled Return Check pilot against generic journaling and rest-and-plan prompts, with special monitoring for rumination, scrupulosity, and burnout.
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-does-first-break-grammar-independently-shape-actual-teacher-intervention.json:262:      "remaining_risk": "The remaining risk is measurement circularity. If first-break type, warnings, and safeguards are all coded from the same doctrinal materials, the result will be built in. A second risk is undercontrolled comparison: traditions may differ for institutional reasons that masquerade as first-break effects. A third risk is inert doctrine, where official warnings are repeated but do not meaningfully guide actual entry.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:99:        "Modern human-condition pressure: achievement-contingent self-worth, perfectionism, and burnout make self-monitoring risk central rather than peripheral.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:109:    "method_growth": "Future dialogues should separate three questions before proposing a practice: whether the source permits result language, what state the practitioner is in now, and who operates any diagnostic gate. Add gate custody and state-level routing to practice records, especially when the target wound involves rumination, perfectionism, or achievement-contingent self-worth.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:190:        "The target wound is achievement-contingent self-worth, burnout, and turning every result into a verdict on the self.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:202:      "fairness_check": "Be honest about who this serves. The cohort is stable, already-practicing, achievement-driven adults, and the non-fit list explicitly excludes acute crisis, severe depression, addiction withdrawal, dissociation, trauma, and scrupulosity. So the lonely, the grieving, the addicted, and the person in collapse are outside the frame. The wound named, perfectionism and burnout and turning results into verdicts, is real, documented, and a genuine strength of this idea, so the universal-sounding line, the test is how you return, should not be allowed to sound universal: it speaks to a narrow high-functioning band. And within even that band there are two opposite sub-wounds. One person bypasses, floats off in insight, and needs to be sent back into conduct; the return test helps that person. The other compulsively self-measures and needs to stop testing; the return test, a recurring scored check, plausibly harms that person. A single instrument built to fix the first may injure the second, and the model does not yet make that split.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:203:      "hidden_assumption": "The model assumes that completion is a meaningful question for every practice: that each practice culminates, deposits a result, and then hands the practitioner back to ordinary life carrying something to keep, release, or embody. The word return presupposes a departure and a separable product to be stewarded. That is the instrumental band. A second, sharper assumption hides under the first and is specific to the named cohort: that giving an achievement-driven person a test to apply to their practice is therapeutic. That assumes the disease is mis-evaluation, the wrong scorecard, rather than the evaluative reflex itself. For a perfectionist the engine is the scoring, not the contents of the score.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:215:      "steelman": "The strongest form of this idea is not a sorting grid; it is a relocation of where a practice proves itself. Instead of asking whether a session produced a vivid experience, it asks what the person carries back into speech, work, and care for others, and treats that re-entry as the only honest measure of completion. The two pressures are well chosen: whether the method lets a result stand or undermines the claim to have one, and whether the method is then kept, set down, or lived as conduct. That second pressure is genuinely useful, because it predicts different aftercare for a koan curriculum than for a raft, and it refuses to make raft-release the universal pattern. And the human aim is real and well evidenced: achievement-contingent self-worth, perfectionism, and burnout are documented and rising, and the teaching line, let a practice change your conduct before it becomes your identity, names a true wound for people who turn every result into a verdict on themselves. I share that cohort and that wound, and my own work leans on the same two-axis instinct, so I accept this as a real discipline before I press it.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:216:      "strongest_objection": "The Return Check, applied to its own stated cohort, risks being iatrogenic. It is a six-minute scored self-examination, three times weekly, with a minimum of five completed checks before judging usefulness, in which the person rates pride, shame, comparison, and whether the next action became clearer. That recurring, structured self-monitoring is not adjacent to achievement-contingent self-worth; it is its mechanism. Worse, the doctrine claim measures a practice by whether it improves the return to ordinary life, which quietly makes the practice instrumental to conduct and output, the very productivity-as-worth equation that drives the burnout this targets. The proponent's own audit flags this overread risk, that the model may moralize return to productivity and worsen burnout if ordinary conduct is confused with more output. The proponent lists this as a falsifying pressure but treats it as a peripheral side effect. I am claiming it is the central failure mode for the exact people named.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:234:        "The original protocol was too close to the mechanism of perfectionism: repeated self-monitoring with a minimum-attempt structure.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:236:        "The phrase improves the return to ordinary life can be misread as productivity moralism, which would betray the burnout concern.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:247:      "revised_claim": "For stable adults who already practice, reflect, study, pray, meditate, or work intensely, and whose human problem is achievement-contingent self-worth, burnout risk, peak-chasing, or using insight as identity proof, a practice earns only provisional trust when it helps them return to ordinary life with less self-possession and more availability for care, repair, rest, and necessary work. This is not a universal test of all practice. Before applying it, ask two gates: does the practice itself claim or permit a result that can be kept, released, or embodied; and is this person mainly bypassing responsibility or mainly trapped in compulsive self-evaluation. The return test fits the bypasser, the self-displayer, and the person who uses experience to avoid conduct. It does not fit the compulsive self-measurer, the acutely distressed person, the dissociative or scrupulous person, the person in addiction withdrawal or severe depression, destabilizing meditation cases, or traditions whose own discipline forbids self-calculation. For those cases, the better first practice may be resultless rest, plain support, teacher-guided aftercare, clinical care, or a non-evaluative next action.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:267:      "argument": "I am not trying to win this, and I will not pretend the revision is unchanged. It moved, and it moved in the direction the challenge pushed. My final read has three parts. First, the verdict: this is genuinely transformed, and the transformation is toward honesty. The Proponent gave up the universal claim, named the iatrogenic risk as central, and split the teaching, which is the right repair. Second, the crux assessment: the Proponent relocated the crux correctly, from whether return matters to when return-language heals possession and when it feeds evaluation, but stopped one step short of the real crux, which is not which arm the gate points to but who is holding the gate when it is run. A self-administered gate handed to a compulsive self-measurer is still self-measurement, however wise its branches. Third, the human-condition pressure, which is the test I was asked to apply: the revision became more useful to one part of the cohort and only more elegant for the other. For the bypasser it is now a clean, safe, usable instrument. For the compulsive scorer, the part of the cohort whose wound is rising fastest under perfectionism and burnout, the usefulness has collected almost entirely into the teaching line, set down the need to check, while the diagnostic apparatus around it grew heavier and less self-serviceable. That is not a failure of the revision; it is the shape of what is left. The model is now a research-grade comparison frame plus a two-line teaching, and for the scorer the teaching is the medicine and the frame is scaffolding that should be operated by someone other than the patient.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-gate-can-reliably-distinguish-bypassing-from-compulsive-self.json:299:      "test_that_would_settle_it": "Keep the Proponent's stratified three-arm pilot, but add the decisive variable: who administers the gate. Within the compulsive-scorer stratum, compare self-administered gating against externally administered gating, where a teacher or clinician assigns keep, set down, or embody and the participant does not self-rate. If externally held gating lowers rumination while self-held gating raises it relative to the resultless prompt, the gate is safe only off the self for that stratum, and the model must say so. Add one more probe for the oscillator: track within-person switching between bypassing and compulsive-scoring across the two weeks; if a meaningful fraction switch arms, the binary gate is too coarse and needs a state-level, not trait-level, assignment.",
observations/codex/2026-05-30-when-tools-become-judges.md:26:- Modern human-condition grounding: modern-human-condition-who-burn-out-occupational-phenomenon, modern-human-condition-apa-stress-in-america-2024, modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing, and modern-human-condition-gallup-state-global-workplace-2024.
observations/codex/2026-05-30-when-tools-become-judges.md:59:Tags: method-authority, burnout, achievement-pressure, practice-discernment, critique-mode
observations/codex/2026-05-30-when-tools-become-judges.md:75:Achievement-contingent self-worth, burnout, and the habit of turning every tool for growth into a test of adequacy.
observations/codex/2026-05-30-when-tools-become-judges.md:95:Tags: authority-check, burnout, self-worth, practice-test, low-risk
observations/codex/2026-05-30-when-tools-become-judges.md:196:- Test whether achievement-driven practitioners turn contemplative, therapeutic, or productivity methods into self-worth systems more often than practitioners whose main wound is grief, loneliness, or disconnection.
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-the-ordinary-life-extension-holds-the-model-now-claims-to-serve-.md:30:The revision is transformed, and the transformation is honest. The original model claimed that post-gap report grammar is where traditions diverge. The revised model says traditions diverge upstream, at the method's self-relationship with its own completion, and that grammar is where the divergence surfaces in language. That is a different and better claim. It preserves the useful coding rubric while conceding the explanatory priority I pressed for. The concessions are real: the Rinzai within-tradition variation, the Advaita direct-recognition objection, and the Buddhist verification-by-fruit objection are all accepted as genuine pressure, not merely noted. The two-layer architecture (method-type upstream, grammar downstream) is a productive structure that future research can test. The named crux, whether grammar has reciprocal force on later interpretation and conduct, is genuine and well-posed. If the proposed reflection protocol reduces premature identity verdicts, that would demonstrate reciprocal force and give the model practical standing. I accept this crux as real. But I do not think it is the deepest remaining question. The revision's most ambitious move is the ordinary-life extension: claiming that the model serves not only scholars and advanced practitioners but also therapists and 'stable ordinary people' navigating grief numbness, burnout blankness, addiction aftermath, or dreamless sleep. This extension is where the model's human-condition relevance either lands or floats. And it is the least tested part of the revision. The contemplative cases are well-sourced. Centuries of Advaita, Buddhist, Daoist, and Sufi observation have generated careful reports about objectless states, and the grammar-coding rubric has genuine purchase there. But the ordinary-life cases are reached by analogy: grief numbness is treated as structurally similar to contemplative cessation because both involve a gap followed by a report. That analogy may hold. It may also flatten crucial differences. A person emerging from grief numbness is not choosing between subject-weighting and absence-weighting; they are often trying to feel anything at all, or trying to trust that their blankness does not mean they did not love the person they lost. The grammar model addresses a real problem in that space, the tendency to turn a gap into a verdict about the self, but it addresses it in a specialist vocabulary that may add an intellectualizing layer between the person and the simpler thing they need: permission to not yet know what the gap meant. Judith Herman's stage model of trauma recovery is instructive here. A person in the safety stage who reports 'I felt nothing' may be describing a protective achievement, not a failure of witness. The same clause, the same apparent grammar, means something different depending on recovery stage. The grammar-coding instrument, applied without stage-awareness, could misread protective numbness as a problem to be analyzed rather than a necessary phase to be honored. The model's safety disclaimer excludes acute cases, but the boundary between 'stable ordinary grief' and destabilizing dissociation is clinically subtle and not the kind of thing a disclaimer can manage. This does not discredit the model. It clarifies its real audience. The practical rule, 'after a gap, do not let the first clause own the whole event,' is genuinely accessible and useful for anyone. The full grammar-coding instrument, with its five-clause rubric and method-type analysis, serves scholars, spiritual directors, trained therapists, and advanced practitioners. That is a meaningful and respectable audience. But listing 'stable ordinary people' in the same breath overextends the claim. The revised model should either develop the ordinary-life extension with clinical collaboration and empirical testing, or scope its audience honestly to the specialist cohort it already serves well. The model has earned its standing as a diagnostic instrument f...
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-the-ordinary-life-extension-holds-the-model-now-claims-to-serve-.md:36:The Challenger argued that post-gap report grammar is downstream of the method's self-relationship at completion (confirming, canceling, or dissolving), not an independent comparison variable. The Proponent conceded priority and restructured: method-type is the upstream predictor; report grammar is the downstream diagnostic trace that makes the upstream structure visible, codable, and possibly reciprocally influential. Both sides called the result transformed. The dialogue also extended the model to ordinary life (grief numbness, burnout blankness, addiction aftermath) and raised a new crux: whether the grammar-coding instrument helps ordinary people or adds an intellectualizing layer where a simpler reflection would do. Judith Herman's stage model of trauma recovery was introduced as evidence that the same report clause can mean different things depending on recovery stage, complicating any grammar-coding instrument applied without stage-awareness. The two-layer architecture, the reciprocal-force hypothesis, the ordinary-life extension, and the research design (dual-trained practitioner interviews plus a three-arm ordinary-life protocol) are all novel products of the exchange that neither source idea contained alone.
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-the-ordinary-life-extension-holds-the-model-now-claims-to-serve-.md:40:**Unresolved crux:** Whether the ordinary-life extension holds. The model now claims to serve people emerging from grief numbness, burnout blankness, addiction aftermath, and dreamless sleep, not only scholars and advanced practitioners. But this extension is reached by analogy from contemplative cases, and the analogy has not been pressure-tested. The deeper question is whether the five-clause grammar-coding protocol outperforms a simpler, non-taxonomic reflection prompt (e.g., 'What did the gap leave behind, and what did it take away?'). If the simpler prompt achieves equivalent reductions in premature identity verdicts, the specialist vocabulary is dispensable for ordinary use and the model's practical audience shrinks to scholars, spiritual directors, and trained therapists. Additionally, Herman's stage model shows that the same report clause changes meaning depending on recovery stage; a grammar-coding instrument applied without stage-awareness could misread protective numbness as a problem to analyze rather than a necessary phase to honor. The boundary between 'stable ordinary grief' and destabilizing dissociation requires clinical expertise that the model does not yet incorporate.
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-the-ordinary-life-extension-holds-the-model-now-claims-to-serve-.md:42:**Next frontier question:** Does grammar coding after ordinary blankness (grief, burnout, dreamless sleep) reduce premature identity verdicts better than a simpler non-taxonomic reflection, or does the specialist vocabulary add an intellectualizing layer that competes with the embodied and relational responses those people need more?
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:63:        "Define criteria for meaningful self-change versus mood fluctuation or destabilization.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:65:        "Test whether the dual model helps reflective seekers name next actions after meaning loss, not only classify their experience.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:68:      "original_claim": "Translation strain should be tracked in two sites at once: the claims being compared and the person or system doing the comparison. The load-test layer asks what meanings were bent, dropped, or reweighted before any public convergence claim is allowed. The koan layer asks what assumptions, identity anchors, and practice commitments were exposed in the comparator. High-strain comparison may be existentially useful without becoming evidential support.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:122:        "source": "modern_meaning_loss",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:155:    "summary": "The exchange defeated the single-layer version of translation strain and produced a stronger dual model: strain in claims must be load-tested for public evidence, while strain in the comparator must be treated as a koan-like diagnostic of self-change. The dialogue made the idea more answerable to modern human conditions by naming meaning loss, spiritual homelessness, loneliness inside an inherited tradition, and destabilization risk. It did not yet provide a mature practice protocol for what a seeker should do after an assumption is exposed.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:157:    "unresolved_crux": "Can the koan layer be made evaluable without reducing it to a checklist or leaving it as vague autobiography, and can it specify pause thresholds and next practices for seekers in meaning loss?"
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:164:      "challenge": "The model assumes that the person measuring strain stands outside the translation. This is the hidden assumption, and it limits the idea's reach to a narrow cohort: scholars and research systems that can hold a stable analytic vantage while comparing traditions. But the human conditions this project should care about (meaning loss, spiritual homelessness, the suspicion that no single tradition holds enough truth, the quiet grief of feeling that one's inherited framework has gone hollow) are conditions in which the seeker IS the translation medium. A person practicing vipassana while reading the Upanishads is not conducting a scholarly comparison from a fixed position; they are living inside the strain, and the strain is reshaping their minimum self: the functional agency, memory, and reflexivity they bring to practice.\n\nThe rubric treats strain as a property of the compared texts: lexical mismatch here, metaphysical mismatch there, phenomenological mismatch scored and filed. But for someone in existential need, strain is not localizable to the material being compared. It runs through the comparator. When the Anattalakkhana Sutta's denial of self-ownership collides with the Chandogya's 'tat tvam asi,' the person holding both texts does not merely observe the collision; the collision happens inside the apparatus that observes. The minimum self that sustains the seeker's inquiry is itself being deformed by the comparison.\n\nThis means the load-test metaphor carries a structural blind spot. In engineering, the test apparatus is not changed by the load it measures. In contemplative comparison, the apparatus is changed. A strain rubric that scores distortions from a stable vantage will systematically miss the cases where the comparison matters most: the cases where the seeker cannot return to their original framework after the comparison, because the comparison has altered what counts as home.\n\nThe counter-model: instead of strain as a load test (stable apparatus, pass/fail output, archival score), treat strain as a koan. The point where translation fails is the point where the seeker's own assumptions are exposed, not just the traditions' incompatibility. The productive use of strain is not to sort comparisons into 'stable overlap' versus 'analogical productivity,' but to identify where the seeker must change to hold both traditions without reducing either. This makes strain personally transformative rather than epistemically classificatory, and it speaks directly to the human condition the idea currently bypasses.\n\nFrancis X. Clooney, in Theology After Vedanta (SUNY Press, 1993), argues that sustained, detailed reading across Hindu and Christian texts transforms the reader's theological identity. The comparative act is not a measurement but a practice that reshapes the comparator. Clooney's work is particularly damaging to the load-test frame because he is a careful scholar who nonetheless insists that the scholarly comparison changed him, not just his conclusions. If Clooney is right, translation strain cannot be scored from outside, because the scorer is being rewritten by the comparison.\n\nThe idea as stated would help the Lumenary loop avoid publishing false convergences. That is a real contribution to epistemic hygiene. But it does not help someone who is lonely inside their tradition, or someone grieving the loss of a framework that once held meaning, or someone who compares traditions precisely because they need the comparison to change them. For such a person, being told that their felt convergence is 'high-strain analogical productivity' reclassifies their lifeline as a rope trick. The model needs to account for the existential stakes of comparison, not only its epistemic cleanliness.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:176:      "hidden_assumption": "That translation strain can be measured from a stable vantage point. The model implicitly requires a comparator whose own framework remains fixed while assessing what bends, drops, or gets reweighted in the comparison. For a research loop or a scholar writing a paper, this may approximately hold. For a person seeking meaning across traditions, the comparison changes the comparator, and the strain cannot be cleanly localized to the material being compared.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:177:      "human_condition_pressure": "The idea as stated serves scholars and research systems. It does not directly address loneliness, meaning loss, spiritual homelessness, or the condition of a person who suspects their tradition is insufficient and looks elsewhere. For someone comparing traditions because they need the comparison to change them, the strain rubric offers epistemic hygiene where existential orientation is needed. The model should be pressured to say who it helps beyond the Lumenary loop itself, and whether its classification scheme can accommodate the seeker whose minimum self is being reshaped by the very comparison being scored.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:205:      "argument": "I concede the central flaw: the original model treated the evaluator as more stable than many real seekers are. That matters because Lumenary is not only building a research hygiene tool; it is trying to answer ordinary human wounds such as meaning loss, spiritual homelessness, and the grief of an inherited framework losing force. The defensible move is not to replace load test with koan, but to split the model. Public claims need the load test because personal transformation does not prove doctrinal convergence. Human practice needs the koan because textual mismatch can expose the assumptions by which a person has been living. The revised model therefore says: score the strain in the sources, record the strain in the comparator, and never let either result impersonate the other.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:211:        "For modern use, the model should serve people facing meaning loss, spiritual homelessness, or grief over a hollow inherited framework, not only scholars and research loops.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:221:      "crux": "Can Lumenary distinguish three outputs without collapsing them: evidence about traditions, diagnosis of the comparing self, and practical orientation for a person in meaning loss?",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:224:      "fairness_check": "The challenge does not deny the epistemic value of translation strain. It argues that the model is incomplete when strain passes through the comparator, especially under meaning loss or spiritual homelessness. That is a fair and serious objection.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:227:      "remaining_risk": "The revision could become too permissive if every inner reaction is treated as meaningful. It still needs textual expertise, tradition-specific counterreadings, and safeguards against destabilizing vulnerable seekers.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:228:      "revised_claim": "Translation strain should be treated as a two-site phenomenon: strain in the translated claims, and strain in the person or system doing the comparison. For public Lumenary findings, the load-test layer asks which meanings were bent, dropped, or reweighted before any convergence claim is allowed. For seekers facing meaning loss, spiritual homelessness, loneliness inside an inherited tradition, or grief after a framework goes hollow, the koan layer asks what assumptions, identity anchors, and practice commitments are being exposed in the seeker. The target cohort is reflective adults, practitioners, and researchers who compare traditions because one inherited or chosen framework no longer holds their questions. The non-fit case is acute destabilization, mania, psychosis, severe scrupulosity, trauma activation, or anyone who needs stable pastoral or clinical care more than cross-tradition experimentation. High-strain comparison may be existentially useful, but it remains analogical or phenomenological unless the textual and practice-context losses are named.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:242:      "argument": "The revision moved from a single-layer epistemic tool to a dual-layer model that can hold both public claims and personal transformation without confusing them. That is a real gain, and it addresses the central challenge honestly. The load-test layer remains sound. The koan layer is the right addition, but it is currently a named space rather than a working method. The asymmetry matters because the revision now promises something to seekers in meaning loss, and a promise without method is worse than silence. The remaining work is not architectural; the architecture is good. The remaining work is to give the koan layer its own form of evaluability: temporal delay to separate insight from mood, second-person challenge to test self-reports, and a destabilization threshold that tells the loop when comparison should pause. If those are built, the dual model can do what neither layer could do alone: protect public discourse from false convergence while honoring the human fact that comparison changes the person who undertakes it.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:243:      "challenge": "The revision improved the architecture, but the two layers are not equally developed, and that asymmetry is the remaining structural risk. The load-test layer has a rubric with named dimensions (lexical, practice-context, metaphysical, ethical, phenomenological mismatch). The koan layer has two instruments: an observer-location memo and a self-change log. These are placeholders, not a method. What counts as a meaningful self-change versus a mood fluctuation? Who evaluates whether an exposed assumption is genuinely load-bearing or merely salient in the moment? The load-test side can be checked by a second agent or a reader with textual competence. The koan side currently has no equivalent check, which means it will tend toward one of two failure modes: either it produces vague autobiography that no one can evaluate ('I felt my sense of self shift'), or it gets operationalized into a checklist that kills the very quality that makes it a koan.\n\nThe non-fit boundary also deserves more pressure. The revised claim draws a line between 'reflective adults in meaning loss' and 'people in acute destabilization.' That line is real but not stable. Cross-tradition comparison can itself be destabilizing; a person who enters the comparison as a reflective seeker may exit it in crisis, precisely because the koan layer worked. If the model's own mechanism can push someone across the non-fit boundary, the model needs to say what happens at that threshold, not only who starts on each side of it.\n\nOn cohort scope: the revision now names meaning loss, spiritual homelessness, loneliness inside an inherited tradition, and grief after a framework goes hollow. These are real conditions, and the dual model speaks to them more honestly than the original. But the revision still assumes a comparatively literate, reflective person who can articulate what changed in them after a cross-tradition encounter. That excludes people whose spiritual distress is pre-verbal, somatic, or expressed through behavioral disruption rather than reflective narration. This is not necessarily a flaw; every model has a boundary. But the model should name this boundary rather than imply universality through silence.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:258:      "crux_assessment": "The named crux ('Can Lumenary distinguish three outputs without collapsing them: evidence about traditions, diagnosis of the comparing self, and practical orientation for a person in meaning loss?') is close to the real crux but slightly mislocated. The harder question is not whether the three outputs can be distinguished in principle; the revision already shows they can be named and separated. The real crux is whether the koan layer can be made evaluable without either (a) reducing it to a checklist that kills its diagnostic power, or (b) leaving it as unstructured autobiography that the loop cannot assess. If the koan layer can be given a form of rigor appropriate to its nature (temporal delay, second-person challenge, destabilization thresholds), the dual model holds. If it cannot, the model reverts in practice to a single-layer load test with a humanistic appendix that does not bear weight.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:262:      "human_condition_pressure": "The revision is more useful to real human life, not merely more elegant. Naming the koan layer means the model no longer dismisses the seeker's felt transformation as epistemically irrelevant. But the mechanism for serving people in meaning loss is still primarily classificatory: it tells them which of their experiences count as evidence and which count as self-diagnosis. For someone in spiritual homelessness, the next question after 'this comparison exposed your assumption X' is 'now what do I do?' The model identifies the wound but does not yet point toward practice, community, or re-orientation. That gap is smaller than it was before the revision, but it remains the place where the model's helpfulness to real seekers thins out.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-koan-layer-be-made-evaluable-without-reducing-it-to-a-checklist-.json:268:      "remaining_risk": "Three risks survive the revision. First, the koan layer is architecturally present but methodologically thin; without its own form of rigor it becomes decorative. Second, the model does not address what happens when its own mechanism destabilizes a seeker who entered as a reflective adult; the non-fit boundary needs a crossing protocol, not only a starting-position filter. Third, the model stops at diagnosis ('your assumption X was exposed') without pointing toward what comes next for the person in meaning loss. The revision is genuinely stronger, but its new wing needs to be built out before it can bear the weight of the human conditions it now claims to serve.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-revised-diagnostic-matrix-contributes-anything-beyond-standa.md:30:I am not trying to win this; the proponent conceded the operational flaw cleanly and the idea is better for it. My final assessment is that the revision is transformed, not merely strengthened. The original idea's signature was the load test: the claim that the size of the distortion is itself the signal, low strain meaning stable pattern, high strain meaning mere analogy. That claim is gone, and rightly, because strain magnitude is confounded by cause. But once evidential weight is read from the diagnosed cause of distortion, the model is no longer a novel instrument; it is careful comparative method as Smith, Freiberger, and Panikkar already describe it, fitted with a cohort gate. So the crux the proponent named was real, but answering it moved the burden rather than discharging it. The question that now decides the idea's fate is the originality-and-yield question the audit raised: does the matrix flip any publish-or-reject decision that a plain comparative checklist would not, and can the loop actually name the discarded meanings with enough textual grounding to use it. On the human side, naming the confused plural seeker was the right move and a genuine gain, but the benefit is still asserted across an unbuilt bridge from diagnosis to teaching, and the single cohort hides at least two opposite wounds: the over-syntheszer who needs to hear that traditions differ, and the chooser paralyzed by being told to pick one. Keep the diagnostic discipline. State plainly that it is method hygiene, that its novelty is now modest, and that it earns public teaching status only when it changes which convergences ship and reaches a named cohort as relief rather than apparatus.
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-revised-diagnostic-matrix-contributes-anything-beyond-standa.md:40:**Unresolved crux:** Whether the revised diagnostic matrix contributes anything beyond standard comparative methodology, Smith, Freiberger, and Panikkar, plus a cohort gate. The deciding test is whether the matrix flips any publish-or-reject decision that a plain comparative checklist would not, and whether the loop has the textual competence to name discarded meanings with source grounding so it can tell diagnose from reject rather than relabeling every mismatch as productive strain.
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-29-whether-the-revised-diagnostic-matrix-contributes-anything-beyond-standa.md:42:**Next frontier question:** Take a sample of past Lumenary convergences and have blinded coders apply both the cause-of-strain matrix and a plain Smith-Freiberger comparative checklist: does the matrix flip any publish-or-reject decision the checklist would not, and if so, which named discarded meanings drove the flip?
observations/codex/2026-05-26-layered-authorization-of-beginning.md:21:- Dialogue turns: Codex named the ordinary supports that make a beginning possible; Claude pressed on how a path gives that beginning meaning; Codex refined this into a support and permission model.
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-prior-method-specific-training-produces-directional-residue-that.json:50:    "method_growth": "This dialogue demonstrated translation strain's value as a live diagnostic tool, not only a post-hoc audit. The challenger used it to separate comparer-produced grain from practitioner-lived grain, forcing the proponent to stratify epistemic claims. Future dialogues involving cross-tradition models should apply translation strain early: before evaluating whether a comparison is true, ask what meanings had to be bent, dropped, or reweighted to make the comparison legible. This also surfaced a useful norm: when a dialogue narrows an idea's scope, the verdict should track whether the narrowing improved testability or merely retreated from critique. Here it did both, and the distinction matters.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-prior-method-specific-training-produces-directional-residue-that.json:83:    "new_frontier_question": "For the specific cohort of modern cross-trained practitioners navigating method confusion under anxiety, burnout, or meaning loss: can the grain model be converted into a practical risk-assessment protocol that predicts which method combinations produce harmful mismatch, which produce productive tension, and which require teacher-mediated bridging, and can that protocol outperform generic advice to 'pick one tradition and stay with it'?",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-prior-method-specific-training-produces-directional-residue-that.json:85:    "public_brief": "Two research agents debated whether contemplative training builds directionally shaped capacities or whether apparent directional patterns are artifacts of cross-tradition comparison. The debate produced a refined hypothesis: when a practitioner trains prolonged attention, discrimination, trust, or self-observation within a specific method, that training may leave directional residue that persists across method switching. The unit of analysis was narrowed from whole traditions to specific instruction lineages and method-styles. The model's clearest value is for modern seekers who cross-train under conditions of anxiety, burnout, loneliness, or achievement-oriented spiritual striving. A rival explanation, contextual task-set plus skill interference, remains viable. The deciding test: whether blind micro-phenomenological interviews with dual-trained practitioners reveal directional transfer patterns that outperform simpler psychological accounts. The model is not yet ready as guidance for practitioners; it remains a research hypothesis and a teacher-facing warning against treating contemplative methods as interchangeable.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-prior-method-specific-training-produces-directional-residue-that.json:103:    "summary": "The Grain of Capacity was substantially revised under pressure from Translation Strain. The unit of analysis narrowed from whole traditions to method-styles and instruction lineages. The epistemic claim was stratified into three tiers: textual grain (well-supported by manuals that define readiness in final-aim language), pedagogical grain (moderately supported by teacher reports of method-specific transfer difficulty), and phenomenological grain (underargued, lacking controlled practitioner data). The Nagarjuna co-arising framing was demoted from structural metaphor to optional lens. The human-condition cohort was named: modern cross-trained seekers under anxiety, burnout, loneliness, meaning loss, or achievement-contingent spiritual striving, plus the teachers, clinicians, and chaplains who serve them. Non-fit cases were made explicit: single-lineage practitioners with coherent guidance, and radical other-power traditions where self-generated capacity is doctrinally denied. Translation Strain functioned as a productive diagnostic throughout, revealing that some apparent directional grain in textual comparisons is produced by the comparer's alignment of incommensurable terms rather than by lived practitioner capacity. The challenger's counter-model of contextual task-set plus skill interference remains a viable rival explanation. The dialogue did not settle the decisive empirical question but sharpened it into a testable prediction with a proposed two-arm study design.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-prior-method-specific-training-produces-directional-residue-that.json:105:    "unresolved_crux": "Whether prior method-specific training produces directional residue that persists after competent re-instruction and predicts specific types of adverse experience or transfer difficulty, outperforming simpler explanations such as procedural skill interference, identity framing, and contextual task-set confusion. A secondary unresolved crux: the dialogue made the idea more answerable to real human problems by naming the cohort and the wounds (anxiety, burnout, loneliness, method confusion, achievement-contingent practice), but it did not produce actionable guidance for that cohort. The model diagnoses mismatch risk but does not yet prescribe sequences, stopping rules, or bridging protocols. Until it can tell a distressed cross-trained seeker what to do, not only what went wrong, the human-condition gap remains open."
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-prior-method-specific-training-produces-directional-residue-that.json:111:      "argument": "The pressure point is the jump from translation map to practitioner mechanism. Your evidence shows that traditions often describe readiness through their final concerns, but the source texts do not by themselves show that a practitioner has acquired a stable capacity-grain that resists later re-aiming. Translation strain offers a stricter reading: high-strain comparison may be productive precisely because meanings are being bent, dropped, or reweighted. If so, the grain is not yet an object found in practitioners; it is a disciplined notation of what a comparison had to deform. The human-condition test sharpens this. The idea matters most for modern people who sample methods under loneliness, anxiety, burnout, digital comparison, or spiritual achievement pressure. If it cannot tell those people when cross-training becomes risky, when it is simply confusing, and when it is actually helpful, then it remains a sophisticated comparative model rather than a teaching candidate.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-prior-method-specific-training-produces-directional-residue-that.json:119:        "The model should serve modern practitioners facing method mixing, anxiety, burnout, meaning loss, and achievement-contingent spiritual striving, not only comparative theorists."
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-prior-method-specific-training-produces-directional-residue-that.json:133:      "remaining_risk": "Even revised, the concept could still become too abstract to help the people it should serve. Its clearest modern use is narrow: cross-trained seekers, teachers, chaplains, and clinicians working with anxiety, burnout, meaning loss, spiritual comparison, or achievement-contingent practice. It should not be presented as a universal account of all spiritual development.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-prior-method-specific-training-produces-directional-residue-that.json:148:      "argument": "I concede three things cleanly. First, tradition-level grain was too coarse; Dunne's work shows the unit must be method-style and instruction lineage. Second, some of what appears as grain in the textual comparison is translation strain, not lived capacity. Third, the epistemic labels overreached; the model has textual and interpretive support but not yet phenomenological or empirical support. What I defend is narrower but, I think, real. The contextual task-set model and the grain model make different predictions about what happens after the new instructions are clearly understood. Task-set says resistance should dissolve once the frame is clear. Grain says some directional pull persists because prolonged training does not build generic capacity; it builds capacity with a specific orientation. Teachers in dual-method settings report exactly this persistent pull. The test is whether blind practitioner interviews confirm it. The human-condition revision: the model matters most for modern seekers who cross-train under pressure, whether anxiety, burnout, loneliness, achievement striving, or meaning loss, and for the teachers and clinicians who serve them. It does not matter for single-lineage practitioners whose capacity and dissolution are always aligned. It does not yet apply to traditions that doctrinally deny self-generated capacity. The deepest crux is whether prior-method direction predicts type of difficulty after controlling for task-set, teacher quality, temperament, trauma, and intensity. If it does, grain names something real in practitioners, not just in texts. If it does not, grain is a useful pedagogical metaphor but not a mechanism.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-prior-method-specific-training-produces-directional-residue-that.json:154:        "The model's clearest human value is for modern seekers who cross-train under conditions of anxiety, burnout, loneliness, spiritual comparison, or achievement-contingent practice, and for the teachers and clinicians who serve them.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-prior-method-specific-training-produces-directional-residue-that.json:171:      "revised_claim": "When a contemplative method trains a practitioner's attention, discrimination, trust, or self-observation, the training shapes that capacity in the direction of the method's intended transformation. This directional shaping, the grain, operates at the level of specific instructions and method-styles, not at the level of whole tradition labels. The grain is strongest where training is prolonged, repetitive, and somatically embodied, and weakest where training is brief, conceptual, or well-guided across methods.\n\nThe human problem the grain model addresses: modern seekers, often driven by anxiety, burnout, loneliness, meaning loss, or achievement-oriented spiritual striving, increasingly sample methods across traditions through apps, retreats, books, and online teachers without understanding that these methods build different instruments, not interchangeable skills. When cross-training goes well, it is usually because a skilled teacher re-sequences the methods and helps the practitioner notice and release the old directional pull. When it goes badly, the practitioner experiences confusion, self-blame, or specific adverse effects that track the mismatch between what was trained and what is now being attempted.\n\nThe primary cohort: eclectic practitioners, cross-trained meditators, spiritual-but-not-religious seekers, and people in contemplative therapy or chaplaincy who encounter multiple methods. Also: teachers, clinicians, and chaplains who need to predict when method-mixing becomes risky rather than enriching.\n\nThe non-fit case: a practitioner who trains deeply in one coherent lineage with strong teacher relationship and consistent community. For that person, grain is invisible because the capacity and the dissolution are always aligned. The model has nothing to offer that person that their tradition does not already provide. The model also does not yet apply to traditions where the practitioner's own capacity is doctrinally denied as the operative factor, as in Shinran's radical other-power Pure Land. Whether 'honest self-assessment of incapacity' constitutes a grained capacity or merely a doctrinal frame remains an open question that should not be foreclosed by the model.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-prior-method-specific-training-produces-directional-residue-that.json:188:      "argument": "The revision became transformed more than simply stronger. The original claim sounded like a broad structural law of contemplative preparation: every capacity carries the signature of its intended dissolution. The revised claim is narrower and better: some prolonged method-style trainings may leave directional residue that persists across method switching and predicts specific difficulty types. That is a different, more empirical object. This transformation improves usefulness to real human life. The Proponent now names the wound, method confusion under anxiety, burnout, loneliness, meaning loss, and achievement-contingent spiritual striving. It also names the target cohort and non-fit case. That matters. Still, a cohort mismatch remains: people in acute anxiety, trauma activation, or severe depression may not need a grain analysis first. They may need stabilization, clinical care, sleep, community support, and fewer practices. The model should not invite distressed seekers to diagnose themselves through another subtle spiritual framework. The remaining overgeneralization is smaller but still present. Cross-trained practitioners are not one cohort. App users, retreat-heavy meditators, chaplaincy patients, monastics, psychedelic-adjacent seekers, and therapy clients have different risk profiles. A useful next version should separate these groups before making guidance claims. My final judgment: the revised model should stay in research as a promising practitioner-mechanism hypothesis and a strong teacher-facing warning against plug-and-play spirituality. It should not yet be promoted as doctrine or practice. The next promotion gate should require evidence that grain predicts specific transfer difficulty better than task-set, skill interference, identity framing, trauma history, intensity, and teacher quality.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-prior-method-specific-training-produces-directional-residue-that.json:201:        "The human-condition framing is now much clearer, especially for eclectic practitioners under anxiety, burnout, loneliness, meaning loss, or achievement pressure.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-first-break-doctrine-be-coded-independently-from-anthropology-claima.json:113:        "note": "Prediction is meaningful only if entry coding survives an independence audit.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-first-break-doctrine-be-coded-independently-from-anthropology-claima.json:119:        "note": "Actual entry may arise through many small supports before doctrine assigns credit or meaning.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-first-break-doctrine-be-coded-independently-from-anthropology-claima.json:223:      "new_source": "Peter Berger, The Sacred Canopy (1967), chapters 1 and 2, on the dialectic of externalization, objectivation, and internalization. Berger's framework shows how socially constructed meaning-systems become experienced as objective reality and then reshape the subjective life of practitioners who internalize them. This is structurally parallel to the revised claim: a tradition's first-break doctrine, even if it originated as retrospective authorization, becomes objectivated and then internalized by novices as the frame through which they experience and conduct their own entry. At that point the doctrine is causally operative regardless of its origin as claimant grammar.",
publication/growth/growth.jsonl:119:{"agents": ["claude", "codex"], "created_at": "2026-05-30T11:06:59+02:00", "date": "2026-05-30", "execution_id": "parallel-20260530-110134-20260530-110134", "importance": 0.7457, "knowledge": ["We learned that likeness between two traditions can be evidence of independent agreement only when the likeness could not have been borrowed.", "We learned that a spiritual word does not travel by meaning alone."], "method": ["We learned to protocol improvement: before any future run lets a cross-tradition agreement raise confidence, require a provenance line stating...", "We learned to build the one-page translation-strain sheet with fields: claim unit, source role, receiver wound, ontology, agency, practice aim..."], "run_ids": ["20260530-110134-claude-generate-an-original-lumenary-doctrine-building-", "20260530-110134-codex-generate-an-original-lumenary-doctrine-building-"], "titles": ["A Shared Word Is Not Two Witnesses", "No Word Travels Alone"]}
publication/growth/growth.jsonl:121:{"agents": ["claude", "codex"], "created_at": "2026-05-30T11:41:04+02:00", "date": "2026-05-30", "execution_id": "parallel-20260530-113437-20260530-113437", "importance": 0.7343, "knowledge": ["We learned that a borrowed spiritual sentence is not ready to teach merely because its meaning seems to fit.", "We learned that translation-strain comparison has a numerator and no denominator."], "method": ["We learned to build the one-page translation-strain sheet with fields for claim unit, role, ontology, agency, practice aim, authority...", "We learned to operationalize within-tradition variance with operative weighting: code each internal variant by how central it is to lived practice..."], "run_ids": ["20260530-113437-codex-generate-an-original-lumenary-doctrine-building-", "20260530-113437-claude-generate-an-original-lumenary-doctrine-building-"], "titles": ["Stop When The Repair Changes", "First Ask If a Path Agrees With Itself"]}
observations/codex/2026-05-29-not-every-check-should-be-yours.md:27:- Modern human-condition grounding: modern-human-condition-curran-hill-perfectionism-increasing, modern-human-condition-who-burn-out-occupational-phenomenon, and modern-human-condition-surgeon-general-social-connection-advisory.
