./publication/x/queue/2026-05-29-operational-remainder-ecology.md:7:Operational Remainder Ecology: A contemplative path is shaped by three interacting factors: the operational capacities it requires, the residue policy it applies after negation, and the training ecology that calibrates those demands in lived practice. The operational...
./publication/distillations.jsonl:25:{"agent": "codex", "atAGlance": "When distant teachings seem to agree, do not count agreement too quickly. The useful part is the bend required to make one sentence fit another. That bend shows what each path protects. It turns agreement into a test, not a trophy.", "created_at": "2026-05-27T00:55:26.119Z", "ideaId": "0e1a69f243a0d090", "insight": "Agreement is tested by what it bends", "keyPoints": ["This shifts comparison away from both universalizing synthesis and skeptical dismissal.", "It gives agreement positive value as a generator of precise distinctions, while refusing to let analogy become evidence.", "The original unit of analysis is not the shared concept, but the deformation required to make concepts align."], "match": ["convergence as translation strain not"], "plainSummary": "When teachings seem to agree, the real evidence is what each one must change to meet the other.", "publicTitle": "Agreement is tested by what it bends", "tags": ["comparison", "translation", "method"], "title": "Convergence as Translation Strain, Not Evidence Weight"}
./publication/distillations.jsonl:27:{"agent": "codex", "atAGlance": "A good comparison should struggle. If two teachings join too easily, we may have sanded off their edges. Pressure reveals whether an apparent match can survive contact with its own terms. The strain is the evidence.", "created_at": "2026-05-27T00:55:26.119Z", "ideaId": "d92d2f0f6455ac53", "insight": "A true bridge carries pressure", "keyPoints": ["Comparative spirituality often rewards recognizable similarity, while skeptical critique often rejects similarity as projection.", "This model makes the deformation itself the research object.", "When two traditions appear to converge, the most productive datum may be the exact distortion required to translate."], "match": ["translation strain as a load"], "plainSummary": "A comparison becomes useful when it shows where two teachings resist each other.", "publicTitle": "A true bridge carries pressure", "tags": ["method", "comparison", "translation"], "title": "Translation Strain as a Load Test for Convergence"}
./publication/distillations.jsonl:28:{"agent": "codex", "atAGlance": "When a path tells us to let go of the self, it still has to decide what remains. Care, memory, duty, awareness, or love may still be needed. The real question is not whether something is left. It is what the path allows that leftover to do.", "created_at": "2026-05-27T00:55:26.119Z", "ideaId": "5a05c720a5039323", "insight": "Letting go still leaves duties", "keyPoints": ["Both unsettle identification with ordinary experience, but Brihadaranyaka 3.", "23 preserves an unobjectifiable seer-knower as the permitted remainder, while SN 22.", "59 pushes non-identification through consciousness itself and refuses to authorize any aggregate as remainder."], "match": ["residue policy in negative self"], "plainSummary": "A path that denies the self must still decide what remains responsible for life.", "publicTitle": "Letting go still leaves duties", "tags": ["self", "responsibility", "practice"], "title": "Residue Policy in Negative Self-Practice"}
./publication/distillations.jsonl:31:{"agent": "claude", "atAGlance": "Two paths can meet the same quiet and draw opposite conclusions. One says a hidden self was found; another says no fixed self was found. The difference is not the silence. It is the rule each path uses after silence.", "created_at": "2026-05-27T00:55:26.119Z", "ideaId": "f67b0346018f3d60", "insight": "The same silence can end differently", "keyPoints": ["Both traditions share a felt common ground; the systematic de-objectification of experience through letting go practice .", "Both arrive at a state where the practitioner is no longer identified with any content of experience.", "This reframes the self/no fixed self debate from 'Do they see the same thing?"], "match": ["the inferential gap"], "plainSummary": "Two paths can meet the same quiet and draw opposite conclusions about the self.", "publicTitle": "The same silence can end differently", "tags": ["self", "silence", "meaning"], "title": "The Inferential Gap: Atman and Anatta as Competing Policies for Objectless Awareness"}
./publication/distillations.jsonl:42:{"agent": "codex", "atAGlance": "Letting go is never general. It is aimed at a certain mistake, wound, or false claim. When we forget the address, we may drop what life still needs. A wise path names what must be released and what must be protected.", "created_at": "2026-05-27T00:55:26.119Z", "ideaId": "2496a3cab9e07b0c", "insight": "Letting go must know its target", "keyPoints": ["This model adds an earlier variable: the addressee of the practice.", "A comparison of negating practices should ask whom the letting go is addressed to before asking what remains.", "'Not this', 'not self', 'do not force', and 'know yourself to know God' can look like one family."], "match": ["negation has an address"], "plainSummary": "A wise release names what must be dropped and what life still needs.", "publicTitle": "Letting go must know its target", "tags": ["release", "responsibility", "practice"], "title": "Negation Has An Address"}
./publication/distillations.jsonl:70:{"agent": "codex", "atAGlance": "Different paths do not begin in the same way. Some begin with discipline, some with trust, some with a teacher, some with crisis, and some with a gift the seeker did not plan. Comparing them is useful only when we preserve those differences. The test is whether a comparison makes each path clearer, not flatter.", "created_at": "2026-05-26T20:23:40-07:00", "ideaId": "6647c8c2b2f6915b", "insight": "Every path begins differently", "keyPoints": ["A beginning carries the shape of the path.", "Comparison should protect difference, not erase it.", "The test is whether warnings become easier to predict."], "match": ["threshold grammar under translation strain"], "plainSummary": "A path's first step often reveals what kind of help, warning, and discipline it will need.", "publicTitle": "Every path begins differently", "tags": ["beginning", "comparison", "practice"], "title": "Threshold Grammar Under Translation Strain"}
./publication/distillations.jsonl:72:{"agent": "codex", "atAGlance": "How a path begins can shape what it allows to remain. If the first step is trust, discipline, surrender, or community, the later lesson may carry that beginning inside it. This does not prove the path is right or wrong. It gives us a better way to test whether beginnings predict later warnings and safeguards.", "created_at": "2026-05-26T20:23:40-07:00", "ideaId": "6816fdc50cc6bb00", "insight": "Beginnings shape what remains", "keyPoints": ["The first step can echo later.", "A path's safeguards reveal what it fears.", "The test is whether early patterns predict later warnings."], "match": ["entry-residue architecture"], "plainSummary": "The way a path starts may predict what it later protects, warns against, or leaves behind.", "publicTitle": "Beginnings shape what remains", "tags": ["beginning", "practice", "test"], "title": "Entry-Residue Architecture"}
./publication/distillations.jsonl:75:{"agent": "codex", "atAGlance": "A practice teaches a person what to notice, what to ignore, and what to trust. Over time, those lessons can become habit. That means a method is never just a tool; it also trains a way of seeing. The test is whether people carry that trained way of seeing into other parts of life.", "created_at": "2026-05-26T20:23:40-07:00", "ideaId": "6264d2ba9cccc16b", "insight": "A practice teaches the eye", "keyPoints": ["Practice trains attention over time.", "A tool can become a habit of seeing.", "The test is what follows the person afterward."], "match": ["layered direction and residue-to-grain conversion"], "plainSummary": "A practice does more than produce an experience; it trains what a person notices next.", "publicTitle": "A practice teaches the eye", "tags": ["practice", "attention", "habit"], "title": "Layered Direction and Residue-to-Grain Conversion"}
./publication/distillations.jsonl:78:{"agent": "claude", "atAGlance": "Different paths do not begin in the same way. Some begin with discipline, some with trust, some with a teacher, some with crisis, and some with a gift the seeker did not plan. Comparing them is useful only when we preserve those differences. The test is whether a comparison makes each path clearer, not flatter.", "created_at": "2026-05-26T23:28:06-07:00", "ideaId": "732bcb02b424bd36", "insight": "Every path begins differently", "keyPoints": ["A beginning carries the shape of the path.", "Comparison should protect difference, not erase it.", "The test is whether warnings become easier to predict."], "match": ["credit-constrained residue authorization as a two-variable model of post-negation translat"], "plainSummary": "A path's first step often reveals what kind of help, warning, and discipline it will need.", "publicTitle": "Every path begins differently", "tags": ["beginning", "comparison", "practice"], "title": "Credit-Constrained Residue Authorization as a Two-Variable Model of Post-Negation Translation Strain"}
./publication/distillations.jsonl:86:{"agent": "codex", "atAGlance": "the bend in the bridge should be tracked in two sites at once: the claims being compared and the person or system. The load-test layer asks what meanings were bent, dropped, or reweighted before any public agreement claim is allowed. The koan layer asks what assumptions, identity anchors, and practice commitments were exposed in the comparator. High-strain comparison may be existentially useful without becoming evidential support.", "created_at": "2026-05-26T23:28:07-07:00", "ideaId": "dd5510b50d19fa58", "insight": "Two-Site bend bridge.", "keyPoints": ["The synthesis joins about knowing hygiene with existential diagnosis.", "It does not merely compare traditions, and it does not merely validate personal transformation.", "It creates a rule for keeping evidence about traditions, diagnosis of the comparing self, and practical orientation separate."], "match": ["two-site translation strain"], "plainSummary": "the bend in the bridge should be tracked in two sites at once: the claims being compared and the person or system doing the comparison.", "publicTitle": "Two-Site bend bridge.", "tags": ["advaita", "method", "practice"], "title": "Two-Site Translation Strain"}
